Comment:
¬†@thepsychicpeach8425¬† yeah, I definitely prefer these darker, more suspenseful movies better, as compared to the bright, colorful, light hearted/comedic Marvel films.
I feel like there's so many great graphic novels that could be adapted to film the way "The Dark Knight" was for Batman.  I was actually reading on my tablet the other day looking for a new book to read, and it recommended the "The Last Ronin", and that other Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles comic/graphic novel.  It made me think that they(or even an original script) would be great candidates for this kind of dark, suspenseful, R-rated/made for adults kind of comic inspired films.  Then again, I was obsessed with TMNT as a kid, so who knows.
Actually, now that I think about it, the first three live action TMNT films(from the early 90s) were kind of "dark" in a way, especially the first one.  The most recent two they made were better than I thought they'd be, but the way they used CGI for the characters instead of actual actors just ruined it for.  It felt like I was watching a cutscene from a video game or something.

Comment:
¬†@willieearles3151¬† That's because this batman still hasn't  created his charismatic, classy, playboy "Bruce Wayne persona" YET, Pattinson was explaining this at the DcFandome panel, that this batman doesn't know how to separate Bruce from Batman, so he gets lost in Batman... it's part of his character arc, his character development, he's gonna have to realize that he needs to create his "Bruce Wayne persona" .This explains his long hair, his seriousness even when he doesn't have his batman suit and it's in public, because even without the suit he's still pretty much Batman and not his alter ego (the playboy Bruce Wayne).. 

This has happen in several Batman comics, in which the character start without that "Bruce Wayne persona" and later on he creates one.

If you watched Tenet (it doesn't matter if you didn't like the movie, if you thought the movie was too confusing, too plot driven, bc I'm only going to mention one scene ) then you know there is a scene where  Pattinson's character, Neil, had to pretend to be a wealthy man, while at the same time he was carefully observing his surroundings, planning an operation on his head, but, keeping his facade, his well trim, elegant, classy and charismatic demeanor. In that scene Neil resembles Bruce Wayne, my point is that Robert knows how to play, a wealthy well trim, elegant/classy and charismatic character, he knows how to be a Bruce Wayne, if he is not doing it here, is because it doesn't serve the story YET because he hasn't created his "Bruce Wayne persona," but  eventually  will do it...  And this is Matt Reeves vision, because he has said so himself, Pattinson is only playing the role in the way Reeves envisioned the character's journey, changing the actor won't change anything, because that other actor will also play Bruce but without the "Bruce Wayne persona", for the first movie because that's Matt Reeves vision. .. And Robert  Pattinson is a handsome man, always was.

Comment: Touch grass. Even the cartoons are better Batman films. This is a pretentious, artsy, pseudo-intellectual mess of a movie that tries too hard to take It self too seriously while being full of stupid and goofy, and most importantly fails at being what Batman movies are meant to be - engaging. Nothing about It feels satisfying, there's nothing original about the plot, there's no character development, by the end everything pretty much stays the same. Now we know that in the next movie Joker will be in It and we're supposed to be super excited about that tease, because It's not like we've seen enough iterations of that character already. Why explore anything different? Just to be clear the movie is not terrible, but it's not the masterpiece people say It is. If you seriously believe that you have a lot of movies to explore.

author: @Nclake5485

Comment:
¬†@Nclake5485¬† I think what the other people are getting at is that the detective work was never the crux. It was a jumping off point or a linking thread. It was there, but the case was always solved as the clues came in. The audience was never guided to wonder about the case like a crime novel would have them. We didn‚Äôt feel as if we were investigating the case with Batman, it was always us watching him solve it. 

The earlier approach worked for many movies because the conflict wasn‚Äôt focused on how the case was solved but more what the solution entailed. We would follow leads but the audience wasn‚Äôt really expected to follow the trail and get that ‚ÄúAHAH‚Äù moment when we finally put it together. There was detective work but not for audience, the audience‚Äôs interest was always on the antagonist‚Äôs plot, not so much figuring out the plot, but just seeing it unfold and how batman would combat it. 

The intrigue was in how to combat the plot but not how to reach it.

Comment: ¬†@k-b9253¬† I think the most interesting part of batman is his anger, the fact that he‚Äôs so close to the line that separates him from the people he fights, but never quite crosses it. I‚Äôm a fan of stories like Arkham asylum serious house, which really exaggerate and showcase Batman‚Äôs broken, tortured mental state, as appose to stories like batman year one which portray a more stoic, stern version of the character. Don‚Äôt get me wrong, I love year one and that version of batman is needed, he‚Äôs great. Just look at 3 of the four Arkham games and the dark knight trilogy, it‚Äôs brilliant, but I guess that‚Äôs the thing, that version of batman is very oversaturated. I think we need more stories like batman Serious house and batman Arkham origins, that really show off the moral and psychological complexities of the character, so I really should have put ‚Äúthis is everything I WANT batman to be‚Äù, as appose to ‚Äúeverything batman should be‚Äù. Another thing to note is, this Batman‚Äôs brutality won‚Äôt be left unexplored like Ben afleck‚Äôs portrayal, which came off as thuggish and not at all like batman; the synopsis of the film indicates that a lot of attention will be put on Batman‚Äôs anger, talking about his struggle between veangence and righteousness, which is personally something I am so hyped for.

Comment:
¬†@sathvik6982¬† that‚Äôs where we disagree. I think Batman is a great character when his strengths are played to and the narrative surrounding him is honest not meta

Batman was created one year after Superman, right at the end of what‚Äôs know as the Golden Age of Detective Fiction but he was already an established character by the time teenage boys fascination moved from the intrepid explorers and detectives of dime store pulp comics like Buck Rogers and The Hardy Boys to the glossy pages of Action Comics and Timely Comics w/ their superhumans in bright patriotic leotards

In fact DC used to literally be Detective Comics. All that is to say that yes Batman is a character of a different age but so is Superman, Wonder Woman, Captain America, X Men etc. I don‚Äôt think that matters. What matters is what you do w/ the characters NOW. Every other comicbook character has stayed true to their origins more or less w/ just updated goals, values and designs to match the changing times. Every character except Batman

I‚Äôm not saying Batman is a bad character what I‚Äôm saying is he deserves a lot more than writers constantly smashing him and other characters together like mis matched action figures w/ the obligatory smile and wink to the audience while they make jokes about none of it making sense. Somehow 82 years of prep time still couldn‚Äôt save him from that

Comment:
A lot of people are saying that they didn't really include new rogues gallery characters because they've all been in previous films. But that's a blatant technicality, comparing the Riddler we've had until now to this one is essentially a different character all-together, as was Catwoman to a lesser degree. Much like the Riddler the Penguin was shown in a far different (and more realistic) light and though we've heard about Falcone in the other movies this is the first time he was actually important to the arching narrative.

Though I will say to everyone stating "I'm glad it wasn't the Joker again" or "They can't do the Joker after Heath Ledger" did like...any of you see the scene between him and the Riddler at the end? It's pretty obvious he'll be coming back so we can never really escape him.

Honestly I want a proper Scarecrow. He was in Nolans films but he was a bit player and his intelligence was really underplayed. Scarecrow rarely works for anyone but himself and in this new, darker take on the IP we could finally get the truly terrifying Scarecrow that we've gotten in the comics.

Yup.  When they announced Pattison for the role I was pissed for all of 20 seconds before I realized just how well he could work in the role, especially for a more pared down Batman movie like this.  

What I love about this so far from all I've seen is that not only is he pared down (even moreso than Nolan's) is that they're really leaning into the goth/horror aspect of Batman's world (quite unlike Nolan's).  This really could be the best of all worlds (early "I built all my gadgets and vehicles" Batman a la the comics and Adam West, Burton's Goth and Nolan's real-ish grounded approach).  Can't wait to see it.

My favourite parts of the trailer (aside from all of it!)
1. THAT SCORE OMG
2. This sort of unhinged Batman. Almost as though he could belong in Arkham with the rest of the crazies
3. This serial killer, Zodiac-esqu Riddler. Really helps this feel more like a detective film with action, which is fitting for someone titled 'the world's greatest detective'
4. The Batmobile. Less flashy and ridiculous than past versions yet not as militaristic as the Tumbler. It's like some ungodly crossover between retro 80s supercar and classic muscle car, with a good helping of Mad Max thrown in for good measure. It remains both sleek and brutish and I am IN LOVE

Comment:
¬†@Bob_99.1¬† Batman 1966 is a wholly different type of Film from The Batman 2022. Even The Batman and The Dark Knight have different approaches, one favoring the crime drama aspect, the other focusing more on action. Batman The animated series is again a different type of story, not as silly as 1966, not as dark as Nolan or Reeves. Then you have the insane take on the character that Frank Miller provides and even here I argue is a difference between the gritty DKR and the absolute insanity that is DKSA or ASB&R. Yet, they all work as Batman. No one would say the Adam West version is no longer Batman, because it's too silly, or the Frank Miller version because it's too violent.
On the other hand, if your take Superman and make him darker and more brooding, it breaks the character. It looks like Superman but lacks something fundamental. Same if you make Blade or Wolverine too silly, they don't work anymore. 
That's what I mean with versatile. And I doubt there is a version that is as silly as Adam West while at the same time as brooding as Frank Miller's version.

Comment:
Bruce Wayne is a traumatized orphan with the weight of his family's business on his shoulders. Being Batman is his way of releasing that stress; the kind of release that an immature young man can't resist or control.

I think this is very believable, and they will likely tame him down as he matures if their focus is on believable character development. He will learn from his enemies what not to be and it will be meaningful since his best foes have some of the same tendencies he does.

Comment:
¬†@christisking835¬† Sure but I‚Äôd saying that Robert Pattinson has EASILY perfect as Batman AND Bruce Wayne aa the BEST of both as he was able to showcase what makes Batman who he is, his trauma. It‚Äôs not really that he‚Äôs ‚Äúdepressed‚Äù in this movie, it‚Äôs that he‚Äôs heavily TRAUMATIZED in it and that‚Äôs the motivation that makes Batman who he is.
He LEARNS how to be better Bruce Wayne AND Batman at the end of this movie, as this was the whole point OF the movie.
Bruce's Trauma has deeply effected his entire life and well being. It's not about trying to portray a "play boy bachelor" at all, it's about showing a gloomy individual whose DEEPLY traumatized from his parent's death that he can't think or do anything else and I LOVE the way how it's done as Bruce can't be batman without his trauma but this still it's consumed his life so much that he's never moved past his parent's passing to have his own life. This Bruce Wayne looks like he's never had a girlfriend, much less slept with another girl, and DESPERATELY needs to leave his house and touch some grass and it's PERFECT! It's COMPLETELY perfect because Batman IS Bruce's trauma, and this movie had to showcase that he's so obsessed with being batman that he forget how to be himself and a proper human being. It's no different from Batman: Year One or Batman: Mask of the Phantasm, Batman IS the Trauma that makes Batman, BATMAN.
Batman's story will ALWAYS be a tragedy at heart as he can never be fully happy to be Batman.
But the point of this movie is showcase how Bruce can LEARN how to grow from that with his interactions with Selina so he can be a human again and learn HOW to be a better Batman for the people of Gotham by not being so full of rage but by being an inspiration of hope and love!

Comment:
Maybe Nolan is a better director and has a better movie overall, but The Batman is a better Batman film. Not a perfect Batman film, not a perfect adaptation, but closer to the source material and who Batman is. 

Nolan's trilogy would‚Äôve been miles better if it didn‚Äôt sometimes stray away from the comics too much. 
There were many great and unique takes on Batman's supporting characters in Nolan's trilogy, but Batman himself was several times ruined and compromised as a character.

Comment: The Nolan movies played a massive part in bringing Batman as a character back into the live action mainstream. The way I see this movie is being a grounded interpretation of what Bruce would have been like in his early days. People respect and loge Batman because of how humans he is, yet in films they expect him to be superhuman. Batman‚Äôs ‚Äòsuperpower‚Äô has always been his wealth as a baseline, but also his relentless determination and ingenuity. In a more grounded fictional world, you can‚Äôt expect him to become a legend overnight. To me this feels like a refreshing portrayal of what Batman and his first steps into greatness would realistically look like, especially in a live action portrayal.

Comment: Thursday, October 31st. The city streets are crowded for the holiday. Even with the rain. Hidden in the chaos is the element, waiting to strike like snakes. And I'm there too. Watching. 2 years of nights have turned me into a nocturnal animal. I must choose my targets carefully. It's a big city. I can't be everywhere. But they don't know where I am. We have a signal now, for when I'm needed. When that light hits the sky, it's not just a call- it's a warning. To them. Fear is a tool. They think I'm hiding in the shadows. But I AM the shadows. I wish I could say I'm making a difference, but I don't know. Murder, robberies, assault- 2 years later, they're all up. And now this. This city's eating itself. Maybe it can't be saved, but i have to try. PUSH MYSELF. These nights all roll together in a rush, Behind the mask. Sometimes in the morning i have to force myself to remember everything that happened.

Comment:
I just watched it for the second time ever last week after seeing it in the theaters.  It‚Äôs up there with Dredd and Blade Runner 2049 for me as far as theater experiences, the only way i describe them is spellbinding.

The depth of this movie is what makes it the best Batman.  Christopher Nolan took it there and the Dark Knight trilogy will stand alone, but this Matt Reaves rendition already set a tone that is already unmatched.  Robert Pattinson blew me away with his take on the tortured, isolative and emotionally stunted person the real Bruce Wayne would have had to be to be true to the character of an orphan child.  Some of the mannerisms were played a little too well it‚Äôs like authentic lyrics from a traumatized artist. 

I felt like this wasn‚Äôt dark just to be dark and it wasn‚Äôt trying to be colorful at all to live up to the hype, but still it was unrelenting in its depictions of the rich history of all the comics, the animated versions, and our real world, the comics are based on, especially right now with mental illness and public corruption coming to ahead. I am excited to see this version develop and really hope they work in the League of Shadows after the Joker in a nod to Nolan, and the immortal Ras lol.

Comment: Wow, so much to say/think about this edition of the Dark Knight. I remember days of classic cartoons featuring Batman, like "Challenge of the Superfriends" and the Adam West Burt Ward TV show with the great color-costumes of live-action pow, and then came Tim Burton and the Animated Series (on Fox), which were watershed! Christopher Nolan and Ben Affleck gave it nice spice no doubt too. This one featuring the Riddler is both eerie, jarring, graphic, dark, pensive, Realism and neo-modern with classic touches here and there. Jeffrey Wright is good in this too, good supporting character IMO. Batman's surpassed Captain America, no? Batman is officially the strangest super-hero out there. I compare this worlds-graphics trend in Batman-media to the turn we saw with classic (Laurel and Hardy) to modern (Farrelly Bros.) comedy imagery...all humanist. Quite cool.

Comment: The Batman, skillfully directed by Matt Reeves, offers a captivating cinematic experience. I appreciate the darker approach Reeves took with Robert Pattinson's portrayal. Drawing inspiration from Tim Burton's iconic Batman films of 1989 and 1992, which established a gothic and brooding atmosphere with Michael Keaton in the lead, Reeves masterfully sets a similar tone. The ensemble cast and crew deliver stellar performances, with Zoe Kravitz shining in her role, Colin Farrell transforming into a mesmerizing Penguin - his portrayal so convincing, one could hardly recognize him - and Jeffrey Wright delivering a compelling performance as James Gordon. It would be intriguing to witness Joaquin Phoenix embody the Joker in a potential sequel, pitting his talents against Pattinson's Batman.
